name: Samay
tweet: Even Microsoft makes mistakes.  If there's one lesson we learned, it's that it always pays to do more due diligence!   And if it seems too good to be true, it probably is...

name: Samay
tweet: My other team members ended up returning the money and that was the end of the story.   I kind of forgot about this experience because I was a little disappointed at the time. Now, I just think it's really funny.

name: Samay
tweet: Now, this made absolutely no sense, because in our introduction call we made it clear that:  (1) we were students (2) this was a hackathon project (3) the GitHub repo + organization (which is how they found us) was not affiliated with any company, just us.

name: Samay
tweet: And that's where the fun ends...  After that, we got a huge email with a bunch of follow-up questions. One of these questions asked for a different product, one that was advertised by a company with a similar name as us.   It was a mix-up.

name: Samay
tweet: We were literally about to license our weekend project to Microsoft for $30k ‚Äî it was crazy.   Finally, after a few weeks, we shipped our deliverable and Microsoft paid out two of our team members $7,500 each to start.  https://t.co/qASnIN8eGA

name: Samay
tweet: We quickly caught the rest of our team up & got on a call with the Microsoft employee who reached out.   We then drafted a "statement of work".   Once they were on board, we got to work over the next few weeks ‚Äî improving the codebase, writing documentation, etc.  https://t.co/ocKhsyGxLd

name: Samay
tweet: $30k was (and still is) an insane amount of money for me. I was a high school senior at the time.   However, there was no way we were worth $30k. All we had was a scrappy prototype that barely worked, but we had our hopes up.  https://t.co/26dwoSkKOH

name: Samay
tweet: After the hackathon, my team members and I didn't really keep in touch until one of them got a LinkedIn DM 1 year later...  A Microsoft employee was offering us $30k to license Camlytics.  https://t.co/HjAWlj3jiG

name: Samay
tweet: In January of 2018, I attended @PennApps, a hackathon at the University of Pennsylvania.   My team and I built Camlytics, a real-time analytics platform for physical spaces given any video input (e.g. security cameras).   It was a decent idea & we had a lot of fun building it.  https://t.co/PBQ8xO31Jt

name: Samay
tweet: more than 130 SPACs have gone public in 2021 already ‚Äî that's more than all of 2019 (!)  @chamath took @virgingalactic, @opendoor, Clover Health, SoFi, & more public through SPACs.   @Kaepernick7 is in on it too ‚Äî he's raising $250M+ for his social justice focused SPAC. üëÄ

name: Samay
tweet: as a result, a private company can go public in weeks and the process is much simpler, compared to a traditional IPO or direct listing.

name: Samay
tweet: the founder of the SPAC then takes the money raised and looks for a target private company to merge with.   they have 2 years to find a target company or the money is returned to investors.

name: Samay
tweet: SPACs have one purpose: merge with a private company, thereby taking it public.   simply put, SPACs ‚Äî special purpose acquisition companies ‚Äî go public on the market as a "shell" company (i.e. it only exists on paper) to raise $$$ from investors.

name: Samay
tweet: time to learn about SPACs üöÄ  I had absolutely no idea what they are so I decided to spend my Saturday evening figuring it all out.   üëá
